h those countries to take their oil?  The whole argument is brain dead.  <br>
The reason Bush is not attacking North Korea is because they already possess nuclear weapons and probably would use them if attacked.  Hence, the idea that we need to take out Iraq right now, before they get nuclear weapons.  We tried to take the North Koreans out in the early 50's and because of a much different geopolitical environment, didn't get the job done.  North Korea has been a problem ever since.  In fact, the reason we're having so many issues with them now is courtesy of Bill Clinton.  Clinton tried to ignore the problem, then got on his knees and appeased North Korea for all of the 90's.<br>
BTW - I'm all for a hydrogen based economy.  It's good for the environment (though - I could really care less about that).  I'm more for the idea that it'll spin off a lot of technology.  Also am for nuclear power plants, fusion technology.  Can someone give me a layman's explanation on why nuclear fusion always seems to be 20 years down the road?  We've been working on it for 40 - 50 years, and never seem to get over the hump.  What gives?   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 265<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 10:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=360.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: War for Oil</span><hr size=1> First off nearly all of our involvement in the Middle East is ultimetly about oil. Without it, the Middle East would be a largely politically ignored region like much of Africa. Ever since the British pulled out in the 1960's, the USA has been the self-proclaimed protector of the middle east, making sure the oild flows. This does not mean that the war is just a ploy for American oil companies to sieze Iraqi oil fields, as that is highly unlikely.<br>
<br>
On fusion, progress has been made, steadily and surely. Current test devices have exceeded the break even point. Ultimetly the successful development of fusion power is tied to other technologies; materials, superconducting magnets, electronics, etc.. As those fieldes advanced, so did fusion technology. It may sound cliche but 25 years from now, fusion does look like it can be a reality. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1067<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/1/03 12:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=360.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: War for Oil</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Can someone give me a layman's explanation on why nuclear fusion always seems to be 20 years down the road? We've been working on it for 40 - 50 years, and never seem to get over the hump. What gives? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
